WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:35.852 --> 00:37.938
(car horn)

00:38.021 --> 00:40.023
(knock at door)

00:41.149 --> 00:43.777
Gilbert, you'd better get up. They're here.

00:43.861 --> 00:46.321
- I'm up.
- You OK?

00:46.405 --> 00:48.657
- Yeah.
- You sure?

00:48.740 --> 00:51.451
Sure I'm sure.

00:53.161 --> 00:56.874
- You remember the first time you left home?
- Yes.

00:56.957 --> 01:00.002
And I was just as scared as you are.

01:00.085 --> 01:04.423
I'm not scared. I just don't like
the idea of leaving you here all alone.

01:04.506 --> 01:08.343
Oh, I'll be fine. I was fine
when you went away to computer camp.

01:09.011 --> 01:11.805
Mom, that was just for two weeks.

01:11.889 --> 01:16.143
I can take care of myself.
I'm much more worried about you.

01:16.226 --> 01:20.814
I'm gonna be just fine. Anyways,
I'm not gonna be alone. I got Lewis.

01:21.815 --> 01:25.527
Gilbert? Come on, rise and shine.

01:25.611 --> 01:28.405
Dad's waiting outside in the car.
It's all packed.

01:28.488 --> 01:30.991
Hi, Flo. It's a beautiful day, isn't it?

01:31.074 --> 01:35.704
It's gonna be a great year.
Now, I figure with lunch and two ARVs,

01:35.787 --> 01:39.791
we should be on the road approximately
7 hours, 18 minutes and 7 seconds.

01:39.875 --> 01:43.378
- ARVs?
- Average restroom visits.

01:43.462 --> 01:44.963
(laughter)

01:45.047 --> 01:47.382
Oh, I'm so proud of you two boys.

01:47.466 --> 01:50.344
Come on, Gilbert. Let's go to college.

01:50.427 --> 01:52.971
(braying laugh)

02:22.751 --> 02:27.005
Hey, Lewis, what time you got?
I'm tryin' to work out our exact ETA.

02:27.089 --> 02:31.301
I got two thirty-seven.
Dad, how fast are we going?

02:31.385 --> 02:34.721
I've got the old cruise control set at 35.

03:06.879 --> 03:09.631
Adams College, home of the Atoms.

03:10.465 --> 03:12.676
Gilbert, this is gonna be really neat.

03:12.759 --> 03:15.429
I sure hope so. What if it isn't, huh?

03:15.512 --> 03:18.390
Don't be so negative.
We'll have the time of our lives.

03:18.473 --> 03:20.976
I'm not being negative. I'm being nervous.

03:21.059 --> 03:23.729
Don't be, cos everything's gonna be great.

03:23.812 --> 03:26.773
- Just like high school, right?
- This is college.

03:26.857 --> 03:31.445
Remember, there are
6,127 students at Adams.

03:31.528 --> 03:34.156
- 58 per cent of which are girls.
- So?

03:34.239 --> 03:37.576
So that's 7,107.32 boobs.

03:37.659 --> 03:39.953
(braying laughter)

03:40.037 --> 03:45.167
You college guys are all alike.
All you really care about is gettin' laid.

03:45.250 --> 03:49.338
- I wish I was goin' with you.
- (braying laugh)

03:51.298 --> 03:52.883
Dad!

03:58.639 --> 04:01.642
(Lewis) Wow! This campus is awesome.

04:02.726 --> 04:07.940
It's a lot bigger than I expected. Maybe
we should have just gone to City Tech, huh?

04:08.023 --> 04:13.445
Tech's nothin'. You know Adams has got
the best computer department in the country.

04:13.529 --> 04:17.115
Yeah, you're right. Adams is the best.

04:40.013 --> 04:43.225
(Mr Skolnick) Well, boys...
I mean "men"...here we are.

04:49.022 --> 04:53.360
What an opportunity for you guys.
You're both gonna do great.

04:53.443 --> 04:57.948
I'm proud of you. Your father would
have been proud of you, too, Gilbert.

04:58.031 --> 05:03.412
I know, Mr Skolnick. Don't tell my mother
I was nervous. I wouldn't want her to worry.

05:03.495 --> 05:05.956
- Of course not. Don't sweat it.
- Thanks.

05:06.039 --> 05:07.624
(cycle bell rings)

05:07.708 --> 05:10.210
Hey, Lewis, come here. Sit down.

05:13.297 --> 05:15.382
I envy you, Lewis.

05:15.465 --> 05:19.094
This is one of the finest institutions
in the country.

05:19.887 --> 05:22.389
You're gonna do fantastic here.

05:24.433 --> 05:26.852
Try not to break too many hearts.

05:26.935 --> 05:29.146
That hasn't been a real problem yet.

05:29.229 --> 05:32.357
Come on, you're gonna make
some lucky girl very happy.

05:32.441 --> 05:35.485
You're smart, easy-going.

05:35.569 --> 05:37.279
Got your father's good looks.

05:37.362 --> 05:39.907
(braying laughter)

05:39.990 --> 05:44.411
And you got a great sense of humour.
I really believe in you, son.

05:44.494 --> 05:48.040
- Thanks, Dad. I won't let you down.
- I know.

05:48.582 --> 05:51.084
Gilbert, help me with the trunk.

05:53.962 --> 05:56.548
- Uh, Gilbert?
- Yes, sir?

05:58.050 --> 06:00.510
College isn't like high school.

06:00.594 --> 06:03.972
You'll be on your own.
I want you to take care of yourself.

06:04.056 --> 06:07.809
I will. Anyway, I won't be alone. I got Lewis.

06:07.893 --> 06:10.270
Besides, we're college men now, right?

06:10.354 --> 06:12.689
- Right.
- Ow.

06:17.611 --> 06:20.030
It's easier gettin' it down.

06:22.115 --> 06:24.701
Hold it, guys. This is an historic moment.

06:25.953 --> 06:27.871
All right, say "cheese".

06:27.955 --> 06:29.706
(both) Cheese!

06:30.040 --> 06:32.501
Got it.

06:32.584 --> 06:34.836
Bye, Dad.

06:35.879 --> 06:38.298
Bye. Thanks for the ride.

06:40.884 --> 06:42.970
(passers-by laugh)

06:49.226 --> 06:51.103
- You OK?
- Yeah.

06:59.111 --> 07:02.865
- (Gilbert) Bye, Mr Skolnick!
- (Lewis) Drive careful, Dad.

07:05.200 --> 07:06.785
(girl) Watch out!

07:08.996 --> 07:11.081
- Sorry.
- Excuse us.

07:16.378 --> 07:19.214
You know, Gilbert, I feel different already.

07:19.298 --> 07:22.342
Like... more mature.

07:22.426 --> 07:24.761
Looks like we're in for quite a change.

07:24.845 --> 07:30.100
I'll say. Parties, meeting new people.
This is really gonna be great.

07:30.183 --> 07:32.811
- I don't know.
- Just relax. Be yourself.

07:32.895 --> 07:37.065
Like Davy Crockett always said -
be sure you're right, then go ahead.

07:41.403 --> 07:45.157
(all chant) Ogre! Ogre! Ogre! Ogre!

07:45.240 --> 07:48.994
- Anyway, college is a whole new ball game.
- Nerds!

07:49.077 --> 07:52.623
- People judge you different than in school.
- Nerds!

07:53.832 --> 07:55.250
Nerds!

07:57.711 --> 07:59.171
Nerds!

07:59.254 --> 08:02.883
- Where are they?
- I think they're talking about us.

08:02.966 --> 08:05.510
- No way.
- Nerds!

08:06.970 --> 08:09.264
- Nerds! Nerds!
- (all chant) Nerds! Nerds!

08:09.348 --> 08:11.725
Come on, Lewis, let's go.

08:11.808 --> 08:13.977
(chanting continues)

08:18.273 --> 08:21.276
(? "Are You Ready" by Ya-Ya)

08:35.332 --> 08:38.376
(man) Ogre!

08:38.460 --> 08:41.046
Fill her up, baby!

08:42.172 --> 08:44.049
All right!

09:01.733 --> 09:06.238
OK, everybody, listen up!
It's time for stair diving!

09:29.094 --> 09:33.724
- Well, Gilbert, here's our new home.
- Can't believe we finally made it.

09:51.867 --> 09:55.287
Lewis, if you don't want
the bed by the window, I'll take it.

09:55.370 --> 09:57.456
- You got it.
- Thanks.

10:04.046 --> 10:08.717
- You know, this is really a great room.
- Yep. Definite possibilities.

10:10.677 --> 10:14.556
Do you think they'd let us put in
a little refrigerator for snacks?

10:14.640 --> 10:19.519
Are you kiddin', Gilbert? We can put
a fridge and a microwave right there.

10:19.603 --> 10:22.689
That'd be a good place
for an entertainment centre, too.

10:22.773 --> 10:25.150
Great.

10:25.234 --> 10:28.862
That's just the beginning.
We'll have the best dorm room on campus.

10:28.946 --> 10:31.990
I don't know about the best.
It'll be the messiest.

10:32.074 --> 10:35.202
Relax, Gilbert. Remember, we got it covered.

10:37.496 --> 10:40.082
This robot will be better than a maid.

10:41.250 --> 10:43.752
It'll help with the women, too.

10:43.835 --> 10:46.255
- Women?
- Yeah.

10:46.338 --> 10:48.590
Let's say one of us is up here with a woman.

10:48.674 --> 10:52.177
This'll be our warning device,
so we don't walk in on each other.

10:52.261 --> 10:56.265
Wait a minute. We're allowed
to have girls in our dorm room?

10:56.348 --> 10:59.685
Not girls, Gil. Women.
We're college men now.

10:59.768 --> 11:03.313
- Isn't college great?
- It's gonna be a great year.

11:06.358 --> 11:09.486
(? "Burning Down The House"
by Talking Heads)

11:11.822 --> 11:14.408
C'mon, Betty. Show me what you got.

11:16.034 --> 11:19.454
Gable, check this out.
Check this out. This is outrageous.

11:19.538 --> 11:22.040
- What is it?
- Just try it.

11:23.250 --> 11:24.918
Oh! You OK?

11:25.002 --> 11:28.297
- Jeez, Burke! What is this?
- 188 proof.

11:28.380 --> 11:33.594
It's called a fireball, man. Watch.
Take that. Flame on, buddy. Flame on!

11:39.016 --> 11:42.269
Yeah! Can you do it again? Do it again.

11:42.352 --> 11:45.981
(they chant) Fireball.
Fireball. Fireball. Fireball.

11:51.236 --> 11:53.989
One more! One more! One more! Fireball.

11:54.072 --> 11:57.576
(they chant) Fireball!
Fireball! Fireball! Fireball!

12:02.915 --> 12:05.000
(all) Oh, shit!

12:10.714 --> 12:14.134
(all)? Our house, our house is burning down

12:14.218 --> 12:18.347
? Our house, our house,
our house is burning down

12:18.555 --> 12:22.226
? Our house, our house,
our house is burning down

12:22.726 --> 12:27.189
? Our house, our house,
our house is burning down

12:28.774 --> 12:33.111
- It must have been the wiring.
- That isn't what the fire department thinks.

12:33.195 --> 12:36.865
Dean, if my boys say it was the wiring,
you gotta believe them.

12:36.949 --> 12:39.493
Dean, school ought to be more careful.

12:40.035 --> 12:45.749
We got a big game comin' up. I don't want my
boys worried about where they're gonna live.

12:45.832 --> 12:49.545
They should have thought of that
before they burnt their house down.

12:49.628 --> 12:53.048
What's done is done.
Where am I gonna put my athletes?

12:53.131 --> 12:56.593
- The freshman dorm?
- What about the students there now?

12:58.428 --> 13:02.516
All right. Thanks to faulty wiring,
we have no place to live. Right?

13:02.599 --> 13:06.436
- (jocks) Right!
- These freshmen are sittin' pretty in there!

13:06.520 --> 13:09.565
- So as of now, that dorm is ours! Right?
- Yeah!

13:09.648 --> 13:12.317
Any room you want. Ready? Break!

13:22.119 --> 13:24.955
Don't come back!

13:25.038 --> 13:27.457
There's your roommate, pal!

13:30.586 --> 13:33.422
If everyone follows directions,

13:33.505 --> 13:38.093
we can manage this move
with as little inconvenience as possible.

13:38.802 --> 13:43.223
All right, men. I want everybody to listen up.
We're movin' out, and I mean now!

13:43.307 --> 13:47.603
Move it! Move it! Move, move, move!

13:52.524 --> 13:54.526
(jock) Get outta here!

13:54.610 --> 13:57.237
(whistle)

13:57.321 --> 14:02.993
All right, listen up. I'm gonna see to it that
each and every one of you is taken care of.

14:03.076 --> 14:07.998
You will be provided with the best possible
food, shelter and accommodation.

14:08.081 --> 14:09.499
(laughter)

14:09.583 --> 14:13.420
- We will try to provide you...
- Now let's move it out!

14:13.503 --> 14:16.715
Move it! Move, move, move! Move it!

14:16.798 --> 14:18.884
(jocks jeer)

14:21.762 --> 14:23.722
Move it!

14:25.182 --> 14:27.017
Get outta here!

14:27.100 --> 14:31.396
(all chant) Nerds! Nerds!
Nerds! Nerds! Nerds! Nerds! Nerds!

14:36.109 --> 14:38.195
(chanting continues)

14:45.452 --> 14:48.455
(Dean) I know this move
has been sudden for all of you,

14:48.539 --> 14:53.210
and you're probably all still very disoriented.

14:53.293 --> 14:59.341
I do want to assure you that this move
is in no way permanent. It's only temporary.

14:59.424 --> 15:05.681
As you see, we've provided accommodations
for you that are... quite acceptable.

15:05.764 --> 15:08.559
It'll be a nice place
for you to enjoy your studies.

15:08.642 --> 15:10.769
(boy) I don't even wanna go to college.

15:10.853 --> 15:14.481
You have a special gift.
You need college to develop it.

15:14.565 --> 15:16.608
I wanna be with people my own age.

15:16.692 --> 15:19.778
You will be with people your own age
when you're older.

15:19.862 --> 15:24.867
But you can't drop me off in a gymnasium.
It looks like we're refugees from a war.

15:24.950 --> 15:28.245
We gotta go now, honey.
Your dad has an appointment.

15:28.328 --> 15:30.414
Bye, son.

15:31.540 --> 15:34.668
(Dean) It is really very comfortable here.

15:36.086 --> 15:39.423
Is there anyone here with allergies?

15:40.173 --> 15:43.594
Me too. Uh, for those of you
who do have allergies,

15:43.677 --> 15:46.013
you can request a foam rubber pillow.

15:46.096 --> 15:50.893
Also, there's a television
for your viewing pleasure.

15:50.976 --> 15:53.770
It is a black and white television.

15:53.854 --> 15:58.650
More good news.
Because of the housing situation,

15:58.734 --> 16:02.571
we are allowing the freshman class
to join and live in fraternities.

16:02.654 --> 16:04.698
(all) Yeah!

16:04.781 --> 16:07.701
The fraternities will select
their members tomorrow.

16:07.784 --> 16:09.161
(whistle)

16:09.244 --> 16:12.998
All right! Enough of this
social bullshit. Grab a cot.

16:13.081 --> 16:15.751
Move it or lose it!

16:17.961 --> 16:20.047
(coach) Go, son.

16:20.130 --> 16:21.673
Move!

16:22.216 --> 16:24.301
Move, move, move, move, move!

16:30.807 --> 16:35.687
(Dean on PA) And the Delta Kappa Gamma
fraternity has selected as its new members

16:35.771 --> 16:39.233
Oliver Scott and Bill Daniels.

16:39.316 --> 16:44.446
(Dean) For those of you
who weren't selected by any fraternities,

16:44.530 --> 16:47.366
you won't be left out in the cold.

16:47.449 --> 16:51.620
You can stay here in the gym
for as long as you like.

16:53.330 --> 16:55.916
Or at least until basketball season.

16:57.417 --> 17:00.212
Please answer when I call out your names.

17:01.630 --> 17:03.715
Poindexter, Arnold.

17:06.260 --> 17:08.053
Latrelle, Lamar.

17:08.136 --> 17:10.638
(effeminately) Lamar Latrelle.

17:12.598 --> 17:14.810
Wormser, Harold.

17:14.893 --> 17:15.978
Present.

17:16.060 --> 17:18.605
Takashi, Toshiro.

17:18.689 --> 17:20.983
Ah, here, sir.

17:22.733 --> 17:25.319
Dawson, Dudley.

17:25.404 --> 17:27.364
Call me "Booger".

17:27.446 --> 17:29.408
All right... Booger.

17:30.200 --> 17:31.827
Rakhim, Raj.

17:31.910 --> 17:36.164
Ah, excuse, please,
but why do they call you "Booger"?

17:36.248 --> 17:38.584
I don't know.

17:39.334 --> 17:41.670
Posquito, Lawrence.

17:44.464 --> 17:46.049
Daniels, Paul.

17:46.133 --> 17:48.844
I knew nobody'd pick us, Lewis.

17:48.927 --> 17:53.140
Gilbert, it's probably not over yet.
There's a fraternity for us.

17:53.223 --> 17:55.225
(Dean) Dooley, Edward.

17:55.642 --> 17:57.728
Yozonski, Yosef.

18:02.316 --> 18:06.445
- Wait a second. Are you sure about this?
- Gilbert, yes. Come on.

18:13.744 --> 18:15.913
(Lewis) Hi, girls.

18:15.996 --> 18:18.707
Are you guys looking to join a sorority?

18:18.790 --> 18:20.626
A sorority?

18:20.709 --> 18:23.212
No!

18:23.295 --> 18:29.509
We need some help. We figured pretty girls
like you might be able to suggest a fraternity.

18:29.593 --> 18:35.182
Choosing the right fraternity can be one of
the most important decisions in a man's life.

18:35.265 --> 18:39.102
- For sure.
- Guys like you have to choose very carefully.

18:39.186 --> 18:42.481
- Definitely.
- Tell us what frat do you think is us.

18:42.564 --> 18:46.151
- You guys are Alpha Betas all the way.
- Totally. For sure.

18:46.235 --> 18:50.572
What? Wait. Aren't Alpha Betas,
like, all jocks and face men?

18:50.656 --> 18:55.869
Yes. But you guys have got that certain
something I know they'd be interested in.

18:55.953 --> 19:00.165
- I'll tell 'em you're coming.
- Should we ask for a particular Alpha Beta?

19:00.249 --> 19:02.918
- Stan Gable.
- And you're?

19:03.585 --> 19:05.504
Betty Childs.

19:06.296 --> 19:08.340
Thank you, Betty. Ms Childs.

19:08.423 --> 19:13.095
Maybe if you're not busy sometime
we could have a cup of coffee or somethin'.

19:13.178 --> 19:15.389
Come on, pal.

19:15.472 --> 19:18.475
(Gilbert) I can't believe you asked her out.

19:18.892 --> 19:23.230
(Lewis) You know, Gilbert, if we get in,
maybe we can have our old room back.

19:23.313 --> 19:26.817
- (Gilbert) These guys will never accept us.
- Why wouldn't they?

19:26.900 --> 19:31.071
These are the Alpha Betas.
They're the football players.

19:31.780 --> 19:34.825
I don't think Ms Childs
would have sent us over here

19:34.908 --> 19:38.161
if she didn't think we had
a decent chance of getting in.

19:39.329 --> 19:41.206
(door creaks)

19:41.290 --> 19:43.292
- (eerily) Yes?
- Hi.

19:43.375 --> 19:47.838
Tell Stan Gable that we're the guys
that Betty Childs sent over.

19:47.921 --> 19:50.465
Follow me, boys.

19:50.549 --> 19:52.634
(door creaks)

19:53.677 --> 19:55.554
Gilbert!

20:23.373 --> 20:25.751
(solemnly) Welcome.

20:25.834 --> 20:27.920
(both) Hi.

20:29.963 --> 20:31.840
(Stan) Hey!

20:33.217 --> 20:36.845
You guys seem pretty cool.
Take these for later.

20:39.431 --> 20:42.267
Rubbers? What do we need rubbers for?

20:42.351 --> 20:44.520
(sheep bleats)

20:47.606 --> 20:49.942
(Stan) Let the initiation begin.

20:50.567 --> 20:53.487
(jock) Have you ever made love to a woman?

20:53.570 --> 20:54.530
- Yes.
- No.

20:54.613 --> 20:56.448
- No.
- Yes.

20:57.991 --> 20:59.451
(jocks) Liars!

21:00.035 --> 21:02.371
(TV) All right, let's go for the burn.

21:02.454 --> 21:05.040
(horrible tuneless scraping)

21:09.962 --> 21:13.215
- OK, Takashi, whaddaya got?
- Oh, I think I have a frush.

21:13.298 --> 21:16.176
- What the fuck is a "frush"?
- A frush.

21:16.260 --> 21:19.221
I got two sevens,
and two sevens beats a frush.

21:19.304 --> 21:20.681
Oh, thank you.

21:20.764 --> 21:23.684
(tuneless violin playing continues)

21:34.069 --> 21:36.822
- Oh!
- Jesus.

21:40.492 --> 21:42.578
(violin stops)

21:47.249 --> 21:52.504
So, getting into a fraternity can be the most
important thing in a man's life, huh?

21:52.588 --> 21:56.049
You know, that cheerleader set us up, Lewis.

21:56.133 --> 22:00.304
I really don't think Betty Childs
is that kind of person, Gilbert.

22:02.723 --> 22:04.850
Hey, Lewis?

22:04.933 --> 22:07.019
What is it, Gilbert?

22:07.978 --> 22:12.316
I'm really sorry that I snapped at you.
This gym's really gettin' to me.

22:12.399 --> 22:14.610
It's OK. I understand.

22:14.693 --> 22:18.906
Tomorrow morning we'll find
a better place to live, OK?

22:18.989 --> 22:21.909
- Good night, Gilbert.
- Good night, Lewis.

22:22.951 --> 22:25.746
- Good night, Lamar.
- Good night, Wormser.

22:25.829 --> 22:29.625
- Good night, Takashi.
- Good night, Poindexter.

22:29.708 --> 22:32.794
- Good night, Booger.
- (loud belch)

22:32.878 --> 22:35.214
(all laugh)

22:39.301 --> 22:40.344
(thud)

22:47.100 --> 22:51.146
Hey, take it easy. The computer's your friend.

22:51.230 --> 22:53.607
I wasn't meant to interface with a machine.

22:53.690 --> 22:56.443
Well, you're just beginning. Relax.

22:57.361 --> 22:59.988
It's no use. It's inhuman.

23:00.072 --> 23:03.450
It's not inhuman.
Only humans can be inhuman.

23:04.284 --> 23:06.203
Here, let me show you.

23:10.958 --> 23:13.293
Working with a computer's great.

23:13.377 --> 23:16.755
I mean, it's godlike, in a way,

23:16.838 --> 23:19.675
cos you can have complete control.

23:22.302 --> 23:24.388
- That's good.
- Thanks.

23:26.473 --> 23:30.727
You know, some people,
they can create with their hands.

23:30.811 --> 23:36.024
But when you're working with a computer,
